Reasoning: The claim that Angiotensin Converting Enzyme (ACE) inhibitors are associated with an increased risk for functional renal insufficiency is strongly supported by the evidence. Paper ID 6157837, "Renal considerations in angiotensin converting enzyme inhibitor therapy: a statement for healthcare professionals from the Council on the Kidney in Cardiovascular Disease and the Council for High Blood Pressure Research of the American Heart Association," explicitly states that "ACE inhibitor therapy can be associated with a syndrome of “functional renal insufficiency”" (Proposition ID: prop_661). The abstract of this paper further elaborates that this acute renal failure (ARF) can occur shortly after initiation of therapy or even after months or years. It also details the pathophysiological mechanisms, noting that ARF is most likely when renal perfusion pressure cannot be sustained due to substantial decreases in mean arterial pressure (MAP) or when glomerular filtration rate (GFR) is highly angiotensin II (Ang II) dependent, such as during extracellular fluid (ECF) volume depletion, high-grade bilateral renal artery stenosis, or stenosis of a dominant or single kidney. The source of this information is a statement from reputable medical councils, lending high credibility to the findings.
